data.content:
## Migration Analysis

Your code is the **timeout enforcement** pattern — a thread runs work, and `Thread.Abort()` kills it if time expires. In .NET 8, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` (SYSLIB0006).

### APIs to remove

| Old API | Problem in .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `thread.Abort()` | `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never thrown |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | `PlatformNotSupportedException` |

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        // CancellationTokenSource is IDisposable — always wrap in using
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            // Task.Run + WaitAsync gives cancellable timeout without Thread.Abort
            return Task.Run(work, cts.Token)
                       .WaitAsync(cts.Token)
                       .GetAwaiter()
                       .GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### If the work itself must observe cancellation

The above solution has one key limitation: `Task.Run` detaches the caller, but **the work lambda keeps running in the background** after timeout. Unlike `Thread.Abort`, cooperative cancellation can't force-stop uncooperative code.

If your `Func<T>` does long-running or looping work, pass the token through:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

    try
    {
        return Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token)
                   .WaitAsync(cts.Token)
                   .GetAwaiter()
                   .GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```

Callers then cooperate:

```csharp
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in largeCollection)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return summary;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---|---|
| **Work keeps running after timeout** | Unlike `Thread.Abort`, cancellation is cooperative. Without token checks, the lambda runs to completion in the background, consuming resources. |
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks internal timers. Always `using`. |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly** | Use `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` to distinguish timeout from external cancellation. |
| **Blocking on async with `.Result`** | Can deadlock in UI/ASP.NET sync contexts. `.GetAwaiter().GetResult()` is safer, but prefer `async` all the way if possible. |
| **Truly uncooperative code** | If you must hard-kill code that can't accept a token (e.g., third-party library), move it to a **child process** and use `Process.Kill()`. There is no in-process equivalent to `Thread.Abort` in modern .NET. |
